const PHASE_DATABASE = {
  name:"Phase 4 · Database",id:"db",icon:"🗄️",phase:"Database",color:"#0891b2",
  sizes:["small","medium","large","hyper"],
  short:"Primary store + cache + search — the most consequential and least reversible decision in your entire system",
  detail:{
    what:"The database layer is the collection of storage systems that hold your application's state — the data that, if lost, would end the business. It typically involves three specialized stores rather than one general-purpose database. (1) Primary transactional store: the source of truth where authoritative data lives — users, orders, payments, inventory. This is your PostgreSQL, MySQL, DynamoDB, or Cassandra. Every write goes here first; every other store derives from it. (2) Cache: a fast in-memory store (Redis, Memcached) holding hot data for sub-millisecond reads, absorbing 80–95% of read traffic so the primary DB isn't overwhelmed. The cache is derived data — if it vanishes, you rebuild it from the primary store. (3) Search index: a purpose-built engine (Elasticsearch, Typesense) optimized for full-text search, fuzzy matching, faceted filtering, and relevance ranking — capabilities that SQL databases handle poorly or not at all. Most non-trivial systems end up with all three because no single database excels at transactional writes, high-throughput reads, AND flexible text search simultaneously. The primary store optimizes for write durability and consistency; the cache optimizes for read speed; the search index optimizes for query flexibility. Trying to make one system do all three results in mediocrity at each. The key mental model: your primary store is the single source of truth. Everything else — caches, search indexes, materialized views, read replicas — is a derived, eventually-consistent copy optimized for a specific access pattern. If in doubt about which store has the 'right' data, it's always the primary store.",
    why:"The database is the most consequential and least reversible decision in system design — and it's not close. Application code can be rewritten in months (companies switch from Ruby to Go, from monolith to microservices, from React to Vue). Database migrations take 6–18 months and carry non-zero data-loss risk. Why? Because the data must be preserved perfectly during the transition — you can't lose a single row of financial data, a single user account, or a single message. This means running two databases in parallel (dual-write), verifying every read returns identical results from both (shadow reads), backfilling historical data, handling the inevitable inconsistencies, and finally cutting over — all while the system serves live traffic 24/7. Choosing the wrong primary store can cap your scale (PostgreSQL struggles past 500K writes/sec without sharding), cap your features (Cassandra can't do ad-hoc JOINs, DynamoDB can't do flexible queries without GSIs), or cap your budget (DynamoDB at $0.25/M writes gets expensive fast at high volume). Choosing the wrong secondary store wastes operational effort on infrastructure you didn't need. The right answer depends on access pattern, not popularity. PostgreSQL is famously underrated — it handles 90% of workloads at small-to-medium scale beautifully, with ACID transactions, rich query capabilities, excellent tooling, and a 25-year track record. MongoDB is famously overused — chosen because 'it's webscale' or 'JSON is easier,' only to discover 6 months later that the data has relationships that need JOINs, and the application is hand-rolling them in code at 10× the complexity and 100× the latency of SQL. Cassandra is famously misunderstood — extraordinary for write-heavy time-series at massive scale, but a terrible choice for a CRUD app that needs ad-hoc queries. Every database is the right answer for some workload and the wrong answer for others. Your job is to match the database to the workload, not to the hype cycle.",
    numbers:"Decision factors (in priority order): (1) Access pattern — how will data be read and written? Key-value lookups → DynamoDB. Complex joins and aggregations → PostgreSQL. Time-series writes → Cassandra/TimescaleDB. Full-text search → Elasticsearch. (2) Scale — how much data, how many operations/sec? <50K TPS and <1TB → PostgreSQL single node handles it. >100K writes/sec → consider Cassandra, DynamoDB, or sharded PostgreSQL. (3) Consistency needs — ACID required? → SQL databases. Eventual OK? → Cassandra, DynamoDB. (4) Team familiarity — a database you know well at 80% fit outperforms a database you don't know at 100% fit. Rough scale ceilings before architectural changes: PostgreSQL single node: ~50K writes/sec on tuned hardware (16-core, NVMe SSD, 128GB RAM), ~200K reads/sec with replicas, ~1–2TB before maintenance becomes painful. MySQL: similar to PostgreSQL. Cassandra: 10K–100K writes/sec per node, scales linearly by adding nodes to 1M+ writes/sec. DynamoDB: effectively unlimited with correct partition key design, but cost grows linearly ($0.25/M writes, $0.05/M reads on-demand). CockroachDB: ~20K–50K writes/sec per node with Raft consensus overhead, but scales horizontally with strong consistency. Golden rule: don't shard or switch databases until you've exhausted the simpler tier. Each step up costs 5–10× more in operational effort, debugging complexity, and team expertise requirements."
  },
  tradeoffs:[
    {axis:"Schema flexibility vs Query power",left:"NoSQL (MongoDB, DynamoDB): schema-per-document, easy to evolve, flexible structure — but no JOINs, no cross-document transactions (or limited), ad-hoc queries are expensive or impossible",right:"SQL (PostgreSQL, MySQL): rigid schema, migration required for changes — but rich queries (JOINs, subqueries, window functions, CTEs), ACID transactions across tables, 40 years of query optimization",pos:0.5},
    {axis:"Scale vs Consistency",left:"Distributed NoSQL (Cassandra, DynamoDB): horizontal scale to millions of ops/sec, tunable consistency, always available — but eventual consistency means stale reads, no cross-partition transactions, limited query patterns",right:"ACID relational (PostgreSQL, MySQL): strong consistency by default, rich transactions, powerful queries — but vertical scaling has a ceiling, and horizontal sharding adds massive complexity",pos:0.5},
    {axis:"Operational simplicity vs Cost control",left:"Managed databases (RDS, Cloud SQL, PlanetScale, DynamoDB): zero operational burden, automatic backups, monitoring, patching — but 2–5× more expensive than self-managed, and you're constrained by the provider's configuration options",right:"Self-managed databases: full control over configuration, version, extensions, and cost — but you own the backups, the patching, the monitoring, the failover, and the 3am pages when it goes down",pos:0.4},
    {axis:"Single-model simplicity vs Polyglot power",left:"One database for everything: simplest to operate, one backup strategy, one monitoring stack, one team's expertise needed — but compromises on performance for specialized access patterns",right:"Multiple specialized databases (polyglot persistence): each access pattern gets the optimal store — but you manage multiple systems, multiple backup strategies, and data consistency across stores becomes your problem",pos:0.5}
  ],
  pitfalls:[
    {name:"Choosing NoSQL because 'it scales' — the most expensive bandwagon in tech",desc:"You picked MongoDB because 'it's webscale' (thank you, 2012 YouTube video). Six months in, your data has relationships you didn't anticipate — users have orders, orders have items, items have reviews, reviews have authors. You're hand-rolling JOINs in application code with N+1 queries, spending 200ms to assemble data that a SQL JOIN would return in 5ms. Your 'schemaless' documents have diverged into 5 different shapes over 2 years because nobody enforced a schema, and queries are unpredictable. PostgreSQL handles 99% of small-to-medium workloads. Start there unless you have a specific, demonstrated reason to choose otherwise. Specific reasons for NoSQL: genuinely unstructured data (event logs with varying fields), write-heavy time-series at massive scale (IoT telemetry), or key-value access patterns where you never need JOINs (session store, shopping cart). 'It might scale better someday' is not a specific reason."},
    {name:"Storing files in the database — the silent backup destroyer",desc:"User avatars, PDFs, video thumbnails stored as BLOBs in PostgreSQL. Each 5MB image bloats the table, pushing hot row data out of the buffer cache (killing query performance for everything else). Backups that took 10 minutes now take 2 hours because they include 50GB of binary data. Replication lag increases because binary data travels through the WAL. And storage costs 10× more per GB in RDS ($0.10–0.23/GB) vs S3 ($0.023/GB). The fix is absolute: file data goes in object storage (S3, GCS, R2). The database stores only the URL/key pointing to the file. This applies to everything larger than ~1KB: images, documents, exports, audio, video."},
    {name:"No connection pooler — the connection exhaustion crisis",desc:"Your application opens 100 database connections per instance. You have 50 instances (autoscaling during peak). That's 5,000 database connections. PostgreSQL performs poorly beyond ~500 concurrent connections (each connection is a separate OS process consuming ~10MB of RAM). At 5,000, PostgreSQL is consuming 50GB just for connection overhead and spending more time context-switching between connections than executing queries. The fix: PgBouncer (the industry-standard PostgreSQL connection pooler). PgBouncer sits between your app and PostgreSQL, multiplexing 5,000 application connections into 50 database connections using transaction-mode pooling. It's free, battle-tested, adds <1ms latency, and is used by virtually every PostgreSQL deployment at scale. Amazon RDS Proxy provides similar functionality as a managed service ($0.015/vCPU-hour). For MySQL: ProxySQL serves the same role."},
    {name:"Caching as the first optimization — papering over the real problem",desc:"Database is slow → add Redis cache → problem 'solved.' But the slow query is slow because of a missing index on a WHERE clause that scans 10M rows. Now you have: a cache layer adding operational complexity, an unindexed query that still runs slow on cache misses, and cache invalidation bugs that will haunt you for years. Always optimize the database first: (1) Enable slow query logging (pg_stat_statements in PostgreSQL — shows cumulative query statistics, the single most valuable PostgreSQL extension). (2) Run EXPLAIN ANALYZE on the top 10 slowest queries. (3) Add indexes where the explain plan shows sequential scans. (4) Rewrite N+1 queries as JOINs or batch queries. These steps often improve performance 10–100×. Add a cache layer only after the database is properly tuned and still can't meet your latency or throughput requirements."},
    {name:"No query timeouts — the lock cascade disaster",desc:"An analyst runs a reporting query that accidentally does a full table scan with a lock (SELECT ... FOR UPDATE on a huge table). The query runs for 30 minutes, holding row locks. Other transactions that need those rows queue up. Connection pool fills. Application starts returning 500 errors. Users can't check out. Revenue stops. All because one query had no timeout. Fix: set statement_timeout in PostgreSQL (e.g., 5000ms for OLTP queries, 30000ms for known-slow paths). Set lock_timeout separately (e.g., 1000ms — if you can't acquire a lock in 1 second, fail rather than wait). Set idle_in_transaction_session_timeout (e.g., 30000ms — kill sessions that open a transaction and then sit idle, holding locks). These three settings prevent an entire class of production incidents."},
    {name:"Not having a read replica from the start",desc:"Your single PostgreSQL instance handles all reads and writes. It works great at 1K RPS. At 10K RPS, write latency starts climbing because reads and writes compete for the same CPU, memory, and I/O. You realize you need a read replica but haven't set one up — provisioning takes 30 minutes, and you're in the middle of an outage. On managed services (RDS, Cloud SQL), adding a read replica is a button click. Do it before you need it: run your read replica from day one so it's warmed up, tested, and ready when traffic grows. The cost is ~2× your DB bill, but the insurance is worth it."},
    {name:"Ignoring database connection lifecycle in your ORM",desc:"Your ORM opens a connection, runs a query, and doesn't close it. Under load, connections leak until the pool is exhausted. Or: your ORM opens a new connection per HTTP request, adding 5–10ms of TCP handshake overhead per request. Understanding your ORM's connection lifecycle is critical: use connection pooling at the application level (most ORMs support it), set maximum pool size to match your database's connection capacity divided by the number of app instances, and always close connections explicitly or use context managers/try-finally blocks."}
  ],
  examples:[
    {name:"Figma's PostgreSQL on a single node — until it wasn't",desc:"Figma ran their entire collaborative design platform on one PostgreSQL instance for years, long past where conventional wisdom said they should shard. They invested in aggressive query optimization, careful indexing, and application-level caching instead. When they eventually hit the single-node ceiling, they built a custom horizontal sharding layer rather than migrating to a distributed database — because the data model was deeply relational and switching to Cassandra or DynamoDB would have required rewriting the entire application. The lesson: vertical scaling (bigger machine + better queries) goes much further than people think. And when it stops being enough, custom sharding on your existing database is often preferable to switching database engines entirely, because you keep your data model, your queries, and your team's expertise."},
    {name:"Discord's Cassandra → ScyllaDB migration",desc:"Discord originally chose Cassandra for message storage — trillions of messages, write-heavy, time-series-shaped. Cassandra worked but had operational pain points: JVM garbage collection pauses caused latency spikes, compaction was unpredictable, and per-node throughput required large clusters. They migrated to ScyllaDB (a Cassandra-compatible database written in C++ with a shard-per-core architecture) and achieved ~3× better per-node performance at lower cost, with more predictable latency (no GC pauses). The migration was possible because ScyllaDB is wire-compatible with Cassandra — same CQL queries, same data model, same drivers. Lesson: the same data model can be served by different engines, and API-compatible alternatives can make migration feasible. Also: JVM-based databases (Cassandra, Elasticsearch) have inherent GC latency issues that C++/Rust alternatives (ScyllaDB, Meilisearch) avoid."},
    {name:"Stack Overflow on SQL Server + aggressive caching",desc:"Stack Overflow serves 1.3 billion page views per month on just a few SQL Server instances plus aggressive multi-layer caching (in-process + Redis + HTTP). They've been vocal that they don't need distributed databases, NoSQL, or microservices — a well-tuned relational database with proper indexing, query optimization, and caching handles their access pattern (read-heavy Q&A content) comfortably. Their database team of ~2 people manages the entire data layer. Counterpoint to the assumption that scale requires distributed databases: caching + read replicas + indexing get you remarkably far before you need to distribute."},
    {name:"Notion's sharded PostgreSQL at billions of blocks",desc:"Notion stores every block (text, image, table, toggle, etc.) in PostgreSQL, sharded by workspace_id. Each workspace's data lives on one shard, so all operations within a workspace are single-shard (no cross-shard JOINs needed). They chose PostgreSQL over a distributed database because the data is deeply relational (blocks reference other blocks, permissions cascade through hierarchies) and PostgreSQL's query optimizer handles these complex queries well. Sharding by workspace provides natural isolation and scaling. Demonstrates that PostgreSQL scales much further than skeptics claim when sharding aligns with access patterns."},
    {name:"Uber's database strategy — polyglot persistence at scale",desc:"Uber uses multiple database engines for different workloads: MySQL (sharded via Schemaless, their custom abstraction) for trip data, Cassandra for high-write telemetry, Redis for caching and real-time geospatial queries, Elasticsearch for search, and a custom time-series database for metrics. Each choice is driven by the specific access pattern of that workload. They don't try to force one database to do everything. This is polyglot persistence done right — each data store handles what it's best at, with a clear understanding of the consistency and operational tradeoffs."}
  ],
  levelUp:[
    {from:"small",to:"medium",trigger:"Single DB CPU >70% sustained at peak, or disk >500GB (maintenance operations become slow), or read latency p99 >200ms despite query optimization",action:"Add a read replica to offload read queries. Enable PgBouncer for connection pooling (multiplexes many app connections into few DB connections). Audit and optimize the top 20 slowest queries using pg_stat_statements. How to do it: (1) On AWS RDS: create a read replica with one click (Console → RDS → Create Read Replica). On self-managed Postgres: set up streaming replication with pg_basebackup. (2) Deploy PgBouncer as a sidecar or standalone: configure it in transaction mode with pool_size = 20–50 (matching your Postgres max_connections / number_of_app_instances). Point your app's read queries at PgBouncer's read-replica pool and writes at the primary pool. (3) Enable pg_stat_statements: add 'pg_stat_statements' to shared_preload_libraries, restart, then query pg_stat_statements ordered by total_time DESC to find the queries consuming the most cumulative time. Add indexes, rewrite N+1 patterns, and add appropriate statement_timeout values."},
    {from:"medium",to:"large",trigger:">100K writes/sec sustained (single primary can't keep up) or disk >5TB (backups take hours, VACUUM is slow) or you need different databases for different access patterns (relational for transactions, wide-column for time-series)",action:"Shard your primary store (Citus for PostgreSQL, Vitess for MySQL) OR introduce a specialized database for specific workloads (Cassandra/ScyllaDB for write-heavy time-series, DynamoDB for key-value at unlimited scale). How to do it for sharding: (1) Choose a shard key that keeps related data together (tenant_id for multi-tenant, user_id for user-centric) — see Phase 5 for detailed shard key design. (2) Deploy Citus (PostgreSQL extension — installs as an extension, no migration needed, supports distributed transactions and JOINs across shards) or Vitess (MySQL proxy — VtGate routes queries to correct shard, supports online schema changes). (3) For polyglot: introduce the secondary store alongside the primary — write to the primary first, then propagate to the secondary via CDC (Debezium) or application-level dual-write. The primary remains the source of truth."},
    {from:"large",to:"hyper",trigger:"Global strong consistency required across continents (financial ledger, inventory) OR >500K TPS (beyond what sharded PostgreSQL/MySQL can handle) OR data exceeds petabyte scale",action:"For global strong consistency: Google Cloud Spanner ($0.90/node-hour, GPS+atomic-clock-based TrueTime for global ordering) or CockroachDB (open-source Spanner-inspired, Raft consensus, ~$0.14/vCPU-hour managed). For maximum write throughput: DynamoDB Global Tables (multi-region active-active with last-writer-wins conflict resolution). For petabyte analytical workloads: separate OLTP from OLAP entirely with a dedicated data warehouse (see Phase 14). How to do it: (1) For Spanner: define your schema in Spanner DDL, configure multi-region instance, and use the Spanner client libraries — Spanner handles distribution, replication, and consistency transparently. (2) For CockroachDB: deploy a multi-region cluster, use LOCALITY-OPTIMIZED tables to pin data to the region where it's most accessed while maintaining global consistency. (3) At this scale, most companies operate multiple database engines for different workloads — accept polyglot persistence and invest in a data platform team to manage the ecosystem."}
  ],
  children:[
    {name:"Primary Store",id:"db-primary",icon:"💾",phase:"Database",color:"#0891b2",
     sizes:["small","medium","large","hyper"],short:"SQL vs NoSQL — the answer depends on your access pattern, not the technology's marketing",
     detail:{
       what:"The primary store is the transactional, source-of-truth database — the system that, if you lost it without backup, would end the company. This is where users, orders, payments, and inventory live. The major categories: SQL/Relational (PostgreSQL, MySQL): data stored in rows within tables with a fixed schema, related through foreign keys, queried with SQL. Supports ACID transactions (Atomicity, Consistency, Isolation, Durability) — meaning a transfer from Account A to Account B either fully succeeds or fully fails, never leaving money in limbo. 40 years of query optimization means the database can find efficient execution plans for complex queries automatically. NoSQL Document (MongoDB, DynamoDB, Firestore): data stored as semi-structured documents (JSON-like) with flexible per-document schema. Accessed primarily by key (document ID) or simple queries. Horizontal scaling is easier because documents are self-contained (no cross-document JOINs needed). Trade-off: no JOINs, limited transactions, application code must handle data relationships. Wide-Column (Cassandra, ScyllaDB, HBase): data stored in rows with dynamic columns, optimized for write-heavy workloads and time-series data. Uses LSM-tree storage engines that buffer writes in memory and flush to disk sequentially — enabling 10–100× higher write throughput than B-tree databases. Trade-off: reads are slower (must merge data from multiple sorted files), no JOINs, limited query flexibility. NewSQL (CockroachDB, TiDB, Google Spanner, YugabyteDB): SQL semantics (schema, transactions, JOINs) with horizontal scaling built in. Achieves this through distributed consensus protocols (Raft, Paxos) that coordinate writes across nodes. Trade-off: higher per-write latency (consensus overhead of 5–50ms) and operational complexity compared to single-node PostgreSQL.",
       why:"This choice determines your data model, your query capabilities, your consistency guarantees, your scaling path, and your team's daily development experience for years. Pick based on access pattern, not buzzwords. The decision framework: (1) If your data has relationships (users → orders → items → reviews) and you need to query across those relationships (show me all orders by users who reviewed this product): SQL. (2) If your data is genuinely document-shaped (each document is self-contained, rarely needs to reference other documents) and you need flexible schema (different documents have different fields): Document store. (3) If your workload is massively write-heavy with time-series characteristics (sensor data, event logs, message history) and you primarily query by time range within a partition: Wide-column. (4) If you need SQL semantics (JOINs, transactions) but also need horizontal scaling across multiple nodes or regions: NewSQL. Most applications have relational data. The internet runs on relationships: users follow users, users create posts, posts have comments, comments have reactions, reactions are by users. SQL databases model this naturally. Choose NoSQL only when your access pattern specifically demands it, not as a default.",
       numbers:"Rough ceilings before you need to change strategy: PostgreSQL single node: ~50K TPS on tuned hardware (16-core, NVMe, 128GB RAM), ~200K reads/sec with replicas, ~1–2TB of data before VACUUM and backup maintenance becomes painful. MySQL: similar to PostgreSQL, often slightly faster for simple reads due to simpler query planner. Cassandra: each node handles 10K–50K writes/sec (3K–10K reads/sec); clusters of 10–100 nodes scale linearly to 500K+ writes/sec. ScyllaDB: 3–10× Cassandra's per-node throughput (C++ vs JVM). DynamoDB: unlimited throughput if partition key is well-designed; cost: $0.25/M writes, $0.05/M reads (on-demand), or ~40% cheaper with provisioned capacity. CockroachDB: ~20K–50K writes/sec per node (Raft consensus adds ~5–15ms latency per write). MongoDB: ~30K–80K ops/sec per replica set, shardable. Cost benchmarks: RDS PostgreSQL db.r6g.large (2 vCPU, 16GB): ~$200/month. DynamoDB at 10K writes/sec sustained: ~$6,500/month (on-demand) or ~$4,000/month (provisioned). Cassandra 3-node cluster on i3.large: ~$500/month self-managed, ~$2,000/month managed (DataStax Astra)."
     },
     tradeoffs:[
       {axis:"Relational vs Document",left:"SQL: JOINs across tables, ACID transactions, 40 years of query optimization, rich ecosystem — but rigid schema requires migrations, and horizontal scaling is complex",right:"NoSQL: flexible per-document schema, easy horizontal scaling, fast key-value access — but no JOINs (application-side assembly), limited transactions, and 'schemaless' eventually becomes 'schema-everywhere-in-code'",pos:0.5},
       {axis:"Operational simplicity vs Unlimited scale",left:"Managed single-node DB (RDS, Cloud SQL): one-click setup, automatic backups, point-in-time recovery, zero operational burden — but has a vertical scaling ceiling (biggest RDS instance is 96 vCPU, 768GB RAM)",right:"Distributed database (Cassandra, DynamoDB, CockroachDB): scales horizontally by adding nodes, handles millions of ops/sec — but operational complexity is 5–10× higher (rebalancing, consistency tuning, partition management)",pos:0.5},
       {axis:"Write optimization vs Read optimization",left:"LSM-tree engines (Cassandra, RocksDB, LevelDB): writes are buffered in memory and flushed sequentially — 10–100× write throughput of B-trees. But reads must merge data from multiple levels (read amplification)",right:"B-tree engines (PostgreSQL, MySQL, InnoDB): reads are index lookups with O(log N) — fast and predictable. But writes require random I/O to update B-tree pages in place, limiting write throughput",pos:0.5}
     ],
     pitfalls:[
       {name:"Premature sharding — solving tomorrow's problem with today's complexity",desc:"You shard at 10K RPS because a blog post said sharding is how you scale. Now every query that touches multiple users requires cross-shard coordination, transactions across shards are impossible (or require Saga patterns), and your ORM's convenient query methods don't work across shard boundaries. Meanwhile, a single well-tuned PostgreSQL instance could handle 50K RPS. Sharding is the last resort, not the first optimization. The scaling ladder: (1) Query optimization (indexes, query rewriting) — free, 2–10× improvement. (2) Connection pooling (PgBouncer) — $0, 2–3× more connections. (3) Read replicas — $200–500/month, offloads all reads. (4) Vertical scaling (bigger instance) — $500–2000/month, 2–4× capacity. (5) Caching (Redis) — $100–500/month, 10–100× read reduction. Only after ALL of these are exhausted should you consider sharding."},
       {name:"JOINs across NoSQL collections — reimplementing SQL in application code",desc:"You chose MongoDB for 'flexibility.' Now you need to display an order with its items, each item's product details, and the customer's shipping address. In SQL: one query with 3 JOINs, 5ms. In MongoDB: fetch order, then fetch each item (N queries), then fetch each product (N more queries), then fetch customer (1 more query). That's 2N+2 queries, 200ms, and fragile application code that reimplements what SQL databases have optimized for 40 years. If your data has relationships and you query across those relationships, use SQL."},
       {name:"Schema-less means schema-everywhere-in-application-code",desc:"MongoDB lets you skip schema design — just throw JSON at it. Fast at first! But 2 years later, you have 5 different shapes of 'user' documents created by 5 different versions of your code. Some have 'name' as a string, some have 'firstName' + 'lastName', some have 'fullName', one has 'name' as an object with 'first' and 'last'. Every query must handle all shapes. Every migration is a full collection scan. The 'flexibility' became a maintenance nightmare. Fix: define and enforce a schema even on schemaless databases. MongoDB has JSON Schema validation. Mongoose (Node.js) enforces schemas in the application layer. DynamoDB has no schema enforcement — be extra disciplined."},
       {name:"Forgetting the slow query log — flying blind in production",desc:"Production gets slow at peak. You don't know which query is the problem — is it the user search? The order listing? The analytics dashboard? Without slow query logging, you're guessing. Always enable slow query logging from day 1 and review it weekly. PostgreSQL: enable pg_stat_statements (tracks cumulative query statistics) and log_min_duration_statement = 100 (logs any query taking >100ms). MySQL: set slow_query_log = 1 and long_query_time = 0.1. Review the top 10 queries by total_time weekly — these are your optimization targets. This is free and takes 5 minutes to set up. There is no excuse for not having it."},
       {name:"Using the same database instance for OLTP and OLAP",desc:"Your application writes orders. Your finance team runs 'SELECT SUM(amount) FROM orders WHERE created_at > ... GROUP BY region, month' on the same database. This analytical query scans millions of rows, consuming CPU and I/O that your transactional queries need. Users see latency spikes every time someone refreshes the dashboard. Fix: run analytical queries on a read replica (free if you already have one), or export data to a dedicated analytical store (BigQuery, Redshift) for heavy queries. Never mix OLTP and OLAP on the same primary instance past 1M rows."}
     ],
     examples:[
       {name:"Notion on sharded PostgreSQL at billions of blocks",desc:"Notion stores all content blocks in PostgreSQL, sharded by workspace_id. Each workspace's data is self-contained on one shard, so all reads and writes for a workspace are local to that shard. They chose PostgreSQL because blocks have deep relational structure (parent-child hierarchies, permissions, references) that SQL handles naturally. Sharding by workspace provides clean isolation — no cross-shard queries needed for normal operations. Demonstrates that PostgreSQL scales much further than many engineers assume, especially when the shard key aligns with the access pattern."},
       {name:"DynamoDB at Amazon — the origin of NoSQL at scale",desc:"Amazon built Dynamo (the paper, 2007) because their relational databases were the bottleneck for the shopping cart during peak traffic. The cart has a simple access pattern (get cart by user_id, put item in cart) with extreme write throughput requirements and a strong preference for availability over consistency (better to have a stale cart than a 503 error). Dynamo was purpose-built for this: unlimited horizontal scale for key-value access, eventual consistency with conflict resolution, always-available writes. This is the textbook case for NoSQL: simple access pattern + extreme write throughput + availability over consistency. If your workload doesn't match this description, you probably don't need DynamoDB."},
       {name:"Instagram's early PostgreSQL journey",desc:"Instagram ran on a single PostgreSQL instance through their explosive growth to 14 million users before the Facebook acquisition in 2012. They invested in aggressive query optimization, connection pooling (PgBouncer), and read replicas rather than switching to a distributed database. Their secret was deep PostgreSQL expertise: they knew how to tune shared_buffers, effective_cache_size, and checkpoint settings for their specific workload. This demonstrates that database expertise — knowing your database deeply — often beats database switching."}
     ],
     sizes_cfg:{
       small:{range:"<10K RPS, <100GB, structured data with relationships",rec:"PostgreSQL. Period. It handles 99% of small-scale workloads: ACID transactions, rich queries (JOINs, CTEs, window functions), JSON support (JSONB for semi-structured data), full-text search (tsvector), geospatial (PostGIS), and a massive ecosystem of extensions. Use managed hosting so you never think about backups, patching, or failover. Don't use MongoDB at small scale unless your data is genuinely unstructured (event logs with wildly varying fields) with no relationships. Technology comparison: AWS RDS PostgreSQL ($0.017–0.10/hr depending on instance — automatic backups, multi-AZ option, read replicas). Supabase (managed Postgres with REST API, auth, and real-time subscriptions built in — excellent for MVPs, free tier includes 500MB storage). PlanetScale (managed MySQL with branching/merge workflow like git — excellent schema change experience, free tier). Neon (serverless Postgres that scales to zero — pay only when active, branching for dev/test). Railway ($5/month for Postgres — simplest managed option). SQLite (embedded, zero-config, perfect for single-server applications — Pieter Levels runs million-dollar businesses on SQLite; Turso offers managed distributed SQLite).",tools:["PostgreSQL (RDS/Supabase/Neon)","MySQL (PlanetScale)","SQLite (Turso)"]},
       medium:{range:"10K–100K RPS, 100GB–10TB, need for read scaling or connection management",rec:"PostgreSQL with read replicas for read-heavy workloads. Aurora PostgreSQL for managed horizontal read scaling (up to 15 read replicas, automatic storage scaling to 128TB). Connection pooling is mandatory at this scale (PgBouncer or RDS Proxy). Consider MongoDB Atlas only if your data is truly document-shaped with no cross-document relationships. CockroachDB if you need multi-region with strong consistency and SQL. Technology comparison: AWS Aurora PostgreSQL (compatible with PostgreSQL, up to 5× throughput of standard PostgreSQL through custom storage layer, up to 128TB auto-scaling storage, 15 read replicas with <20ms replication lag — $0.10–0.40/ACU-hour for serverless). MongoDB Atlas (managed MongoDB, auto-sharding, flexible schema, built-in full-text search via Atlas Search — $0.10/hr for M10 cluster). CockroachDB Cloud (managed, distributed SQL, multi-region with strong consistency — $0.14/vCPU-hour, excellent for geo-distributed apps). PgBouncer (free connection pooler, essential for PostgreSQL at scale) vs RDS Proxy ($0.015/vCPU-hour, managed alternative).",tools:["Aurora PostgreSQL","PostgreSQL + PgBouncer","MongoDB Atlas","CockroachDB Cloud"]},
       large:{range:"100K–500K RPS, >10TB, multiple access patterns requiring specialized stores",rec:"This is where polyglot persistence typically begins. Shard your relational data (Citus for PostgreSQL, Vitess for MySQL) for write-heavy relational workloads. Introduce wide-column stores for write-heavy time-series (Cassandra/ScyllaDB). Keep SQL for complex queries. Multi-store architecture: SQL for transactions + Cassandra for time-series + Redis for cache + Elasticsearch for search. Technology comparison: Citus (PostgreSQL extension for horizontal sharding — distributes tables across nodes, supports distributed JOINs and transactions, can be added to existing Postgres; used by Microsoft, Algolia). Vitess (MySQL sharding proxy — built by YouTube, used by Slack, GitHub, HubSpot; VtGate routes queries, supports online schema changes). Cassandra (wide-column, write-optimized, ~10K–50K writes/sec/node; used by Apple, Netflix, Discord — weakness: JVM GC pauses cause latency spikes). ScyllaDB (Cassandra-compatible, C++, 3–10× per-node perf — no GC issues). TiDB (MySQL-compatible distributed SQL from PingCAP — horizontal scaling with strong consistency; used by BookMyShow, Zhihu). DynamoDB (unlimited scale for key-value, $0.25/M writes — expensive at high volume but zero ops).",tools:["Citus (sharded Postgres)","Vitess (sharded MySQL)","Cassandra/ScyllaDB","DynamoDB","TiDB"]},
       hyper:{range:">500K RPS, >1PB, global distribution with strong consistency requirements",rec:"At this scale, database choice is workload-specific and most systems use multiple engines. For globally consistent relational data: Google Cloud Spanner (the only database that provides global strong consistency via GPS-synchronized clocks — used by Google Ads, which can't tolerate billing inconsistencies). For globally available key-value: DynamoDB Global Tables (multi-region active-active with last-writer-wins conflict resolution — used by Amazon.com for cart/session). For massive write throughput: Cassandra at hundreds of nodes (used by Apple for 10PB+ across 75K+ nodes). Technology comparison: Spanner ($0.90/node-hour, global strong consistency, SQL, horizontal scaling — the most expensive but most capable globally consistent database). CockroachDB multi-region (open-source Spanner alternative, Raft-based, ~$0.14/vCPU-hour managed — 2–3× cheaper than Spanner but doesn't have TrueTime, so consistency latency is slightly higher for cross-region transactions). DynamoDB Global Tables (per-region $0.000975/WRU for replicated writes — significantly cheaper than Spanner for eventual-consistency-OK workloads). Custom storage engines: at extreme scale, companies build purpose-built storage (Facebook's RocksDB-based systems, Google's Bigtable, Amazon's internal databases) because no off-the-shelf solution optimizes for their specific access pattern at petabyte scale.",tools:["Google Spanner","CockroachDB multi-region","DynamoDB Global Tables","Cassandra (DataStax)","custom storage engines"]}
     },
     levelUp:[
       {from:"small",to:"medium",trigger:"Single DB CPU >70% sustained or disk >500GB or connection count approaching PostgreSQL's limit (~500 concurrent)",action:"Add a read replica to offload read queries (on RDS: one-click, takes ~30 minutes to provision and sync). Deploy PgBouncer for connection pooling. Vertical scale to a larger instance if CPU-bound. How to do it: (1) Create read replica in your cloud console. (2) Update application: route write queries (INSERT/UPDATE/DELETE) to the primary, read queries (SELECT) to the replica. Most ORMs support primary/replica routing: Rails has built-in database switching, Django has django-read-replica, SQLAlchemy has routing strategies. (3) Install PgBouncer between your app and databases: configure transaction-mode pooling, set default_pool_size to match your DB's max_connections divided by the number of PgBouncer instances. (4) Audit slow queries: SELECT query, calls, total_time, mean_time FROM pg_stat_statements ORDER BY total_time DESC LIMIT 20 — optimize the top offenders with indexes and query rewrites."},
       {from:"medium",to:"large",trigger:">100K writes/sec (single primary is saturated) or disk >5TB (maintenance operations take hours) or single server's biggest available instance can't handle the load",action:"Shard the primary store or introduce a specialized database for the access pattern that's bottlenecking. How to do it for Citus (PostgreSQL): (1) CREATE EXTENSION citus on your existing PostgreSQL. (2) Add worker nodes: SELECT citus_add_node('worker-1', 5432). (3) Distribute your largest tables: SELECT create_distributed_table('orders', 'tenant_id'). (4) Your existing SQL queries work — Citus's query planner routes them to the correct shards. For Vitess (MySQL): (1) Deploy VtGate (proxy) and VtTablet (per-shard agent). (2) Define your VSchema (which tables are sharded, by which key). (3) VtGate intercepts SQL queries, routes to correct shard, and aggregates results. For adding Cassandra: (1) Define your Cassandra schema based on your query patterns (in Cassandra, you design tables for queries, not for entities). (2) Write to Cassandra via the application or via CDC (Debezium from PostgreSQL → Kafka → Cassandra consumer). (3) Read time-series data from Cassandra; continue reading relational data from PostgreSQL."},
       {from:"large",to:"hyper",trigger:"Global consistency required (financial data across continents) OR >500K TPS (beyond sharded single-engine capacity) OR petabyte-scale storage",action:"Deploy a globally distributed database (Spanner or CockroachDB) for data requiring global consistency, or DynamoDB Global Tables for data where eventual consistency is acceptable. How to do it for Spanner: (1) Create a multi-region instance configuration (e.g., nam-eur-asia1 for global). (2) Define your schema in Spanner DDL — interleaved tables for parent-child data locality. (3) Use Spanner client libraries — they handle routing, retries, and transaction coordination automatically. (4) For existing applications: this is a full data migration using the dual-write pattern (see Phase 21). For CockroachDB multi-region: (1) Deploy nodes in 3+ regions. (2) Configure locality-optimized tables: ALTER TABLE orders SET LOCALITY REGIONAL BY ROW — each row is pinned to a region but globally readable. (3) Transactions within a region are fast (~5ms); cross-region transactions pay consensus latency (~50–100ms). Plan your data model to minimize cross-region transactions."}
     ],
     children:[]},

    {name:"Caching Layer",id:"db-cache",icon:"⚡",phase:"Database",color:"#0891b2",
     sizes:["small","medium","large","hyper"],short:"None → Redis → Cluster → Multi-tier (L1/L2/CDN) — the amplifier that makes everything else work",
     detail:{
       what:"A cache is a fast in-memory store that holds frequently-read data, returning it without hitting the slower primary database. Reading from cache takes 0.1–0.5ms; reading from a database takes 5–50ms. That 50–500× speed difference, applied to 80–95% of your reads, is the difference between a fast system and a slow one — and between needing 5 database nodes and needing 50. The cache layer involves four key decisions: (1) What to cache: session data, user profiles, computed aggregations, rendered HTML fragments, API responses, feature flags, hot database rows — anything that's read frequently and changes infrequently relative to read rate. (2) Cache pattern: cache-aside (application reads cache first, on miss reads DB and writes to cache — the most common pattern), read-through (cache itself fetches from DB on miss — simpler application code, but cache must know about DB), write-through (writes go to cache AND DB simultaneously — cache is always fresh, but every write pays cache latency), write-behind (writes go to cache first, asynchronously flushed to DB — fastest writes, but data loss risk if cache crashes before flush). (3) Invalidation strategy: TTL-based (cache entries expire after a fixed duration — simplest, accepts bounded staleness), explicit invalidation (application deletes/updates cache entry when the underlying data changes — freshest, but every write path must remember to invalidate), write-through (cache is always updated on write — no staleness, but more complex write path). (4) Cache topology: single node (simple, one server), cluster (multiple shards for horizontal scaling and HA), multi-tier (L1 in-process cache for <1μs access + L2 distributed cache for shared state + L3 CDN for HTTP-level caching at the edge). The golden rule of caching: the cache is always derived data. The database is always the source of truth. If the cache disappears entirely (Redis restarts, memory evicted), the system must continue to function — slower, but correctly — by falling through to the database.",
       why:"Caching is the single most impactful performance optimization in most systems. Consider a typical API endpoint that queries the database for a user profile: without cache, 100K requests/sec means 100K database queries/sec — you need a large, expensive, heavily-tuned database cluster. With a cache serving 95% of reads (95% hit rate), you need only 5K database queries/sec — a single well-tuned PostgreSQL instance handles this comfortably. You've reduced your database infrastructure by 20× with one abstraction layer. Caching also solves the 'hot key' problem: when a celebrity posts on social media, 10 million users try to read that post simultaneously. Without cache, 10M requests hit the database — which melts. With cache, 1 request hits the database, the result is cached, and the next 9,999,999 requests are served from memory in 0.1ms. The cache absorbs the storm; the database never notices it. But caching comes with real costs: (1) Cache invalidation — 'there are only two hard things in computer science: cache invalidation and naming things.' When the underlying data changes, the cached copy becomes stale. Your invalidation strategy determines how stale data can get and how complex your write paths become. (2) Cache stampede — when a popular key expires, hundreds of concurrent requests simultaneously miss the cache and flood the database. (3) Memory costs — Redis at $36/GB/month adds up when you're caching terabytes. (4) Operational complexity — another system to monitor, alert on, back up (or not), and understand failure modes of. Add a cache when the database is the proven bottleneck and you've already optimized queries. Don't add it preemptively.",
       numbers:"Target cache hit rate: >80% for the cache to justify its complexity. Ideally >95% for maximum database load reduction. Below 80%, most requests still hit the DB, and the cache is adding complexity for minimal benefit. Memory sizing heuristic: cache should hold the 'working set' — the 20% of data that serves 80% of reads (Pareto principle). Don't cache all data; cache hot data. Measure by tracking access frequency per key. TTL guidelines by data type: session data = 30min–24hr (depends on session length), user profile = 5–15min (changes infrequently, but changes should be visible quickly), product catalog = 1–4hr (updated by batch, staleness OK), computed leaderboard = 30s–5min (recomputed frequently), feature flags = 30s (short TTL ensures changes propagate quickly). Cost: ElastiCache Redis ~$0.05/GB-hour ≈ $36/GB/month. Upstash (serverless Redis) = $0.2/100K commands, pay-per-use. Redis Cloud by Redis Labs = $0.03/GB-hour for smaller instances. Dragonfly (Redis-compatible, multi-threaded) = self-hosted, ~25× Redis throughput on same hardware — emerging alternative. Latency comparison: Redis (in-memory, single-threaded but pipelined): p99 <1ms for GET/SET. Memcached (in-memory, multi-threaded): p99 <1ms, slightly faster for simple GET/SET but no data structures. In-process cache (Caffeine for Java, lru-cache for Python): p99 <0.01ms (no network hop) but not shared across instances."
     },
     tradeoffs:[
       {axis:"Hit rate (freshness tradeoff) vs Cache complexity",left:"Long TTL (hours): very high hit rate, minimal DB load, but data can be stale for hours — a user changes their name and sees the old name for an hour",right:"Short TTL (seconds): data is always nearly fresh, but hit rate drops (more cache misses = more DB load), partially defeating the purpose of caching",pos:0.5},
       {axis:"L1 (in-process) vs L2 (distributed)",left:"L1 in-process cache: fastest possible (0.01ms, no network hop), zero external dependencies — but each instance has its own copy (memory waste), and invalidation across instances is hard (instance A updates data, instance B's L1 still has old version)",right:"L2 distributed cache (Redis): shared across all instances (consistent view), one copy of each cached value — but adds a network hop (0.5ms), a dependency on Redis, and a potential SPOF if Redis goes down",pos:0.5},
       {axis:"Cache-aside vs Write-through",left:"Cache-aside: application manages cache explicitly — read from cache, on miss read from DB and populate cache. Simple to understand, lazy population (only caches what's actually requested). But write paths must remember to invalidate/update the cache — miss one and you have stale data",right:"Write-through: every write updates both cache and DB atomically. Cache is always fresh — no stale data. But every write pays cache latency, writes populate cache even for data that may never be read, and the write path is more complex (what if the cache write succeeds but DB write fails?)",pos:0.5}
     ],
     pitfalls:[
       {name:"Cache stampede / thundering herd — the mass migration to the database",desc:"A popular key (e.g., the homepage banner, a trending product) is cached with a 5-minute TTL. When the TTL expires, 10,000 concurrent requests simultaneously discover the cache is empty, all 10,000 hit the database to rebuild it, and the database melts under the sudden load. The stampede can cascade: the DB slows down, requests time out, more requests pile up, and the system collapses. Three proven mitigations (use all three together): (1) Probabilistic early refresh: each request has a random chance of refreshing the cache slightly before the TTL expires, so the key is refreshed before it actually expires. Implementation: if (random() < probability && ttl_remaining < threshold) refresh_cache(). (2) Single-flight / request coalescing: when a cache miss occurs, only ONE request fetches from the DB; all other concurrent requests for the same key wait for that one request's result. Libraries: singleflight (Go), promise-memoize (Node), redis-lock-based (acquire lock, fetch, release lock, others wait). (3) Staggered TTLs with jitter: instead of TTL=300s, use TTL=300 + random(0, 60) so different keys for the same data type expire at different times, spreading the miss load."},
       {name:"Caching everything — diminishing returns and wasted memory",desc:"'Cache all the things!' You cache every database query result. 80% of those cached values are accessed once and then expire — you're spending Redis memory to cache data nobody ever reads twice. The Pareto principle applies strongly: 20% of your data is responsible for 80% of your reads. Cache only what's actually hot. How to identify hot data: enable Redis monitoring (MONITOR command for real-time, INFO stats for aggregate), log cache hits/misses per key pattern, and look at the hit rate per key prefix. If a key pattern has <50% hit rate, it's not worth caching — remove it and save the memory for data that's actually hot."},
       {name:"No invalidation strategy — the 'stale data for days' surprise",desc:"You cache a user's profile with TTL=24h. The user changes their email address. The database is updated, but the cache still has the old email. For up to 24 hours, the user sees their old email everywhere. If you cache a product price and the price changes, customers see stale prices for hours — potentially buying at the wrong price. The fix: decide your invalidation strategy upfront and apply it consistently. Option A: TTL-based (accept bounded staleness — set TTL short enough that the max stale window is acceptable, e.g., 5min for user data, 1hr for catalog). Option B: Explicit invalidation on write (whenever you write to the DB, also delete the cache key — guarantees freshness but requires discipline in every write path; miss one and you have stale data). Option C: Write-through (write to cache and DB together — most complex but freshest). Most systems use TTL + explicit invalidation: set a reasonable TTL as a safety net, AND invalidate on write for the most important data. This gives you freshness when the write path works correctly, and bounded staleness (the TTL) when invalidation is missed."},
       {name:"Cache as source of truth — the data-loss catastrophe",desc:"Developer writes code that updates the cache but forgets to update the database — or the DB write fails silently and only the cache has the new data. The system works fine until Redis restarts, or the key is evicted due to memory pressure, or the TTL expires. Then the data is gone forever — it was never persisted to the database. The rule is absolute: the database is ALWAYS the source of truth. The cache is ALWAYS a derived copy. If the cache disappears entirely, the system must continue to function correctly (slower, but correctly) by falling back to the database. Never write to the cache without first writing to (or reading from) the database."},
       {name:"Serializing complex objects — the deserialization tax",desc:"You cache a user's entire profile including their 200 orders, each with 10 line items, serialized as a 5MB JSON blob. Every cache hit requires deserializing 5MB of JSON — taking 50ms of CPU time, which defeats the purpose of caching (you wanted to save the 5ms DB query and instead spent 50ms deserializing). Cache small, atomic values: cache the user profile (1KB), cache order summaries separately (0.5KB each), and compose them in application code. If the serialized cache value exceeds ~100KB, reconsider what you're caching."},
       {name:"Not monitoring cache hit rate and miss patterns",desc:"You added Redis 6 months ago. You assume it's helping. You've never looked at the hit rate. In reality, it's 40% — barely better than no cache. Most requests are still hitting the database. But you've added Redis as a dependency, added cache invalidation code, and are paying $200/month for it. Monitor hit rate continuously (redis-cli INFO stats shows hits/misses). Alert if hit rate drops below 80%. Investigate misses: are you caching the wrong keys? Is the TTL too short? Is the working set too large for your cache memory?"}
     ],
     examples:[
       {name:"Twitter's timeline cache — cache IS the architecture",desc:"Each user's home timeline is precomputed and stored in Redis. When you open Twitter, the app fetches your timeline from Redis — an O(1) cache hit in <1ms. The timeline is assembled asynchronously: when someone you follow tweets, a background process (fan-out on write) inserts that tweet into every follower's cached timeline. This means reads are trivially fast (just read from Redis) at the cost of expensive writes (fan-out to millions of followers for popular accounts). The cache isn't an optimization — it IS the read architecture. A cache miss means assembling the timeline from scratch by querying tweets from all followed accounts, ranking them, and returning the result — a process that takes seconds, not milliseconds. This is why Twitter invested so heavily in cache reliability: if Redis goes down, Twitter is effectively down."},
       {name:"Facebook's memcached at unprecedented scale",desc:"Facebook operated one of the largest memcached deployments in history: thousands of memcached servers holding hundreds of terabytes of cached data, serving billions of requests per second. They published multiple papers describing the challenges: cache invalidation across datacenters (invalidations are published via McRouter, Facebook's custom proxy), lease-based stampede prevention (a cache miss returns a 'lease token' that only one client can use to populate the cache), and regional consistency (reads from a datacenter go to that DC's cache, but cache invalidation must propagate to all DCs). The papers (Scaling Memcache at Facebook, TAO) are essential reading for anyone building cache infrastructure at scale. Key insight: at Facebook's scale, memcached IS the database for reads — the actual MySQL databases serve primarily as the durable backing store, not the query path."},
       {name:"Cloudflare's tiered caching — L1 + L2 + origin",desc:"Cloudflare uses a multi-tier caching architecture: L1 is the edge PoP (300+ locations, closest to users — serves cached HTTP responses in <10ms), L2 is a regional 'shield' cache (reduces load on origin by coalescing requests from multiple PoPs), and origin is the customer's actual server (only hit on L2 cache miss). This tiered approach achieves >95% hit rates for popular content, reducing origin load by 20× and serving users in <10ms globally. The pattern is applicable to any application: L1 in-process (fastest, per-instance), L2 Redis (shared, cross-instance), L3 CDN (global, HTTP-level)."}
     ],
     sizes_cfg:{
       small:{range:"No cache needed, or simple in-process cache for specific hot paths",rec:"Start WITHOUT a cache. Seriously. If your database handles your load with acceptable latency, a cache adds complexity for zero benefit. The most common premature optimization in web development is adding Redis before tuning the database. Only add cache when: DB p99 latency >100ms AND you've already added indexes and optimized slow queries, OR DB CPU is >60% sustained AND most queries are read-heavy (>10:1 R/W ratio). When you do add cache, start with a single Redis instance. Technology choices: Redis single node (ElastiCache in AWS — $13/month for cache.t3.micro with 0.5GB; Upstash for serverless Redis — free for 10K commands/day; Railway for simple managed Redis). Memcached (simpler than Redis, slightly faster for pure GET/SET, but no data structures, no persistence — only choose if you need nothing beyond simple key-value caching). In-process LRU cache (Python functools.lru_cache, Node lru-cache, Go groupcache — fastest possible, zero dependencies, but per-instance only and not shared).",tools:["Redis single node (ElastiCache/Upstash)","Memcached","in-process LRU"]},
       medium:{range:"Single Redis instance, caching hot paths and session data",rec:"Redis for session storage, hot database rows, computed aggregations, and rate limiting counters. Use the cache-aside pattern (read from cache → on miss, read from DB → populate cache). TTL-based invalidation for most data (5–30min TTL depending on freshness requirements). Explicit invalidation on write for critical data (user profile, inventory count). Monitor hit rate in your observability platform — alert if <80%. Technology comparison: Redis 7 (latest — adds Redis Functions for server-side scripting, improves cluster performance). ElastiCache (AWS managed Redis — automatic failover, backups, patching; $0.017–0.10/hr depending on instance). Dragonfly DB (Redis-compatible, multi-threaded C++ — claims 25× Redis throughput on same hardware, emerging but gaining traction; self-hosted only for now). Upstash (serverless Redis — pay-per-request, auto-scales, no instance management; excellent for variable workloads). KeyDB (Redis fork, multi-threaded — 2–5× Redis throughput; less well-known but production-ready). For cache client libraries: ioredis (Node.js — the standard, supports Redis Cluster, pipelining, Lua scripting), redis-py (Python), go-redis (Go), Jedis/Lettuce (Java — Lettuce is async and recommended for modern apps).",tools:["Redis 7 (ElastiCache)","Dragonfly DB","Upstash","ioredis/redis-py/go-redis"]},
       large:{range:"Redis Cluster for horizontal scaling and HA, with stampede prevention",rec:"Redis Cluster (multiple shards, automatic failover, linear read/write scaling). Separate Redis instances per use case to prevent interference: one for sessions, one for hot data cache, one for rate limiting. Implement all three stampede prevention techniques (probabilistic early refresh, single-flight, jitter on TTLs). Use read-through cache pattern for consistency-critical paths. Technology: Redis Cluster (partitions data across 3–1000+ nodes using hash slots — 16,384 slots distributed across nodes; each node handles a subset of keys). Twemproxy (Twitter's Redis proxy — adds consistent hashing and connection pooling in front of multiple Redis instances; simpler than Redis Cluster but manual sharding). For stampede prevention: implement using Redis locks (SET key NX EX 5 for distributed locking) or the singleflight pattern in your application. For monitoring: Redis SLOWLOG, INFO commandstats, and your APM's Redis integration (Datadog Redis integration is excellent).",tools:["Redis Cluster","Twemproxy","distributed lock for stampede","per-use-case Redis instances"]},
       hyper:{range:"Multi-tier: L1 (in-process) + L2 (distributed Redis) + L3 (CDN)",rec:"Three tiers, each serving a different speed/scope: L1 in-process cache per application instance (Caffeine for Java — ~10μs per get, 99.999th percentile — the fastest possible, but per-instance and limited by heap size; Python lru_cache; Go ristretto). L2 distributed Redis Cluster (shared across all instances — ~0.5ms per get, consistent view, handles invalidation). L3 CDN for HTTP-level caching (Cloudflare/CloudFront/Fastly — serves cacheable API responses and static content from edge PoPs at <10ms globally). Write invalidation must cascade through all three tiers: when data changes, (1) invalidate L2 Redis key, (2) broadcast invalidation to all app instances to clear L1 (use Redis Pub/Sub or a dedicated invalidation bus), (3) purge CDN cache for affected URLs (each CDN has a purge API). Technology: Caffeine (Java — near-optimal in-memory cache based on W-TinyLFU admission policy, maintained by Ben Manes; Google Guava Cache's successor). For L1→L2 fallthrough: implement a multi-level cache wrapper that checks L1 first, then L2, then DB. For invalidation: use Redis Pub/Sub (publish invalidation events on a 'cache-invalidation' channel; each instance subscribes and clears its L1). This is how Facebook's TAO works — a multi-tier cache with a structured invalidation protocol.",tools:["Caffeine (Java L1)","ristretto (Go L1)","Redis Cluster (L2)","CDN (L3)","Redis Pub/Sub for invalidation"]}
     },
     levelUp:[
       {from:"small",to:"medium",trigger:"DB read latency p99 >100ms despite query optimization, OR DB CPU >60% sustained with a read-heavy workload (>5:1 R/W ratio)",action:"Add Redis for caching the hottest data. Start with the cache-aside pattern and TTL-based invalidation (30-minute TTL as a default — adjust based on freshness requirements). How to do it: (1) Provision Redis: ElastiCache (AWS) or Upstash (serverless). (2) Install a Redis client library (ioredis for Node, redis-py for Python). (3) Identify your top 5 most-frequent read queries (use pg_stat_statements). (4) For each, add cache-aside logic: check Redis first (GET user:42), on miss, query DB, then populate Redis (SET user:42 '{...}' EX 1800 for 30min TTL). (5) Monitor: track cache hit rate (hits / (hits + misses)) — alert if <80%. Track Redis memory usage — alert if >80% of configured maxmemory. (6) Add explicit cache invalidation in write paths: when user 42 updates their profile, DEL user:42 from Redis."},
       {from:"medium",to:"large",trigger:"Single Redis instance memory >80% used, OR cache stampede incidents (multiple simultaneous DB hits for the same expired key), OR single Redis instance throughput becomes a bottleneck (>100K ops/sec)",action:"Migrate to Redis Cluster for horizontal scaling and HA. Implement cache stampede prevention. Separate Redis instances per use case. How to do it: (1) Deploy Redis Cluster with 6+ nodes (3 masters + 3 replicas for HA). Use ElastiCache Redis Cluster or self-deploy with redis-cli --cluster create. (2) Update your Redis client to cluster-aware mode (ioredis and most clients support this natively — just change the connection config). (3) Implement stampede prevention: wrap your cache-aside logic with a distributed lock (SET cache-lock:user:42 NX EX 5 — only one process populates the cache, others wait or serve stale). (4) Create separate Redis instances: 'session-redis' for sessions, 'cache-redis' for data cache, 'rate-redis' for rate limiting — different eviction policies, different memory limits, different monitoring thresholds."},
       {from:"large",to:"hyper",trigger:"Redis Cluster read latency >5ms at p99 (network round-trip is becoming significant), OR cache complexity across many services is unmanageable (each service has its own caching logic), OR you need sub-millisecond reads globally",action:"Implement multi-tier caching (L1 + L2 + CDN) with a unified invalidation protocol. How to do it: (1) Add L1 in-process cache using Caffeine (Java), ristretto (Go), or a simple LRU (Node/Python). Set L1 TTL very short (30s–2min) to limit staleness. Set L1 max size to ~10% of heap. (2) L1 checks first; on miss, check L2 (Redis Cluster); on miss, query DB and populate both L2 and L1. (3) For invalidation: when data changes, publish to a Redis Pub/Sub channel 'invalidation:{type}'. Each app instance subscribes and clears its L1. Redis Cluster clears L2 via DEL. CDN purges via API call. (4) For CDN caching: set Cache-Control headers on cacheable API responses (Cache-Control: public, max-age=300, stale-while-revalidate=60). Use Surrogate-Key headers (Fastly) or Cache-Tag headers (Cloudflare) for targeted purging. (5) Build a cache management dashboard: hit rate per tier (L1, L2, CDN), memory usage per tier, invalidation latency (time from write to all tiers refreshed), and top-N hottest keys."}
     ],
     children:[]},

    {name:"Search Layer",id:"db-search",icon:"🔍",phase:"Database",color:"#0891b2",
     sizes:["small","medium","large","hyper"],short:"DB LIKE → Postgres FTS → Elasticsearch → custom search — add only when search is a real product feature",
     detail:{
       what:"A search index is a specialized data structure optimized for full-text search, fuzzy matching, faceted filtering, relevance ranking, autocomplete, and geospatial queries. It's built around inverted indexes: instead of the B-tree approach (given a record ID, find the record), an inverted index maps words to the list of documents containing them (given the word 'kubernetes,' return all documents mentioning it — ranked by relevance). This fundamental difference is why search engines can find 'kubernetes' in 10 million documents in 10ms while SQL LIKE '%kubernetes%' takes 30 seconds — LIKE does a full table scan, checking every row; the inverted index does a direct lookup. Modern search engines add: BM25 ranking (a probabilistic relevance algorithm that considers term frequency, inverse document frequency, and document length), fuzzy matching (find 'kubernetes' even if the user typed 'kuberntes'), stemming (match 'running' when searching 'run'), synonyms (match 'automobile' when searching 'car'), faceted filtering (filter by category, price range, date, etc. with count per facet), autocomplete/suggest (type-ahead as the user types), and highlighting (show the matching text snippet with the search term bolded). These capabilities are fundamentally outside what SQL databases can provide efficiently — SQL was designed for structured data retrieval, not relevance-ranked text search.",
       why:"SQL LIKE '%search_term%' does a full table scan — it checks every single row in the table, comparing the search term character by character. This is O(N) where N is the number of rows times the average field length. At 10K records, it takes maybe 100ms — noticeable but tolerable. At 1M records, it takes 5–10 seconds — unacceptable for interactive use. At 100M records, it takes minutes. And LIKE '%...%' can't handle: relevance ranking (which result is MOST relevant?), typos/fuzzy matching (user typed 'jvascript' — did they mean 'javascript'?), stemming (searching 'running' should find 'run,' 'ran,' 'runner'), faceted counts (how many results per category?), or spatial search (find restaurants within 5km). A purpose-built search engine handles all of these in 10–50ms on 100M+ documents. But search engines are operationally heavier than a plain database — they're another system to manage, monitor, and keep in sync. Only adopt one when search is a real product feature that users interact with, not as a premature optimization for a filtered list that SQL handles fine with proper indexes.",
       numbers:"PostgreSQL full-text search (tsvector/tsquery): works well up to ~5M documents for simple queries, with GIN indexes. Performance: 10–50ms for simple full-text queries on 1M docs. Limitations: no built-in fuzzy matching (pg_trgm extension adds it), no BM25 ranking (basic ts_rank is simpler), no faceting. Good enough for 'search within my app' when search isn't the core feature. Elasticsearch cluster (industry standard): 10K–100K queries/sec depending on query complexity, indexing rate 10K–100K docs/sec per node. Latency: 10–50ms for typical queries on 10M–100M documents. Shard sizing: 20–40GB per shard is the sweet spot. Each shard has fixed overhead (file handles, memory for segment metadata) — too many small shards (1GB each) wastes overhead, too few large shards (200GB each) makes queries slow and reindexing painful. Typical cluster: 3 nodes minimum (for HA — Elasticsearch requires a quorum), production clusters commonly 6–50 nodes. Operational cost: significant — Elasticsearch is a distributed system with its own cluster management (master election, shard allocation, rebalancing), JVM tuning requirements, and a tendency to OOM if not properly sized. Cloud pricing: Elastic Cloud ~$95/month for a basic production cluster; AWS OpenSearch ~$0.03/hr per node (db.t3.small)."
     },
     tradeoffs:[
       {axis:"Simplicity (no extra infra) vs Search power",left:"PostgreSQL FTS: no additional infrastructure, no sync to keep, queries via SQL, backed by your existing DB backups and monitoring — but limited relevance ranking, no fuzzy matching without extensions, no faceting, and performance degrades past ~5M docs",right:"Elasticsearch: powerful relevance ranking (BM25), fuzzy matching, faceting, autocomplete, geospatial, custom analyzers for every language — but adds a separate distributed system to operate, monitor, and keep in sync with your primary DB",pos:0.5},
       {axis:"Real-time indexing vs Throughput",left:"Synchronous indexing (update search index in the API write path): search results are always fresh — but the write path inherits the search engine's latency and reliability. If Elasticsearch is slow or down, your writes slow down or fail",right:"Asynchronous indexing (write to DB, CDC/queue propagates to search index): write path is fast and unaffected by search engine health — but search results are stale by seconds to minutes (the propagation delay)",pos:0.5},
       {axis:"Managed vs Self-hosted search",left:"Managed (Algolia, Elastic Cloud, Typesense Cloud): zero ops, great developer experience, SLA-backed — but expensive at scale ($1/1K search requests for Algolia) and limited customization",right:"Self-hosted (Elasticsearch, OpenSearch, Meilisearch): full control, cheaper at scale, custom analyzers and plugins — but you own the cluster management, scaling, monitoring, and upgrade path",pos:0.5}
     ],
     pitfalls:[
       {name:"Search index as primary store — the durability trap",desc:"Elasticsearch stores data durably in practice, but it's designed as a secondary index — not a transactional source of truth. It doesn't have ACID transactions, its write acknowledgment semantics are 'eventually indexed,' and its data model (immutable segments merged in background) means updates are delete+reinsert. Treating it as the primary store means: no transactions, eventual consistency on writes, and a risk that a segment corruption or bad merge loses data without recovery. Always: the database is the source of truth for your data. Elasticsearch (or any search engine) is a derived index — built from the primary store, rebuildable from scratch if needed."},
       {name:"Synchronous indexing in the write path — coupling your uptime to search",desc:"Every write to your database synchronously writes to Elasticsearch in the same request. Now your API's write latency includes Elasticsearch's indexing latency (~10–50ms), and if Elasticsearch is down or slow, your writes fail or slow down — even though the primary data operation succeeded. Fix: decouple with async indexing. Write to the DB, publish a change event (via CDC/Debezium or application-level event), and a consumer indexes it into Elasticsearch. The search index is 1–10 seconds behind the DB — acceptable for search use cases (a product added 5 seconds ago not appearing in search results is fine)."},
       {name:"Reindexing causes outages — the schema change nightmare",desc:"You change your search analyzer (e.g., adding a synonym dictionary) or mapping (adding a new field). Elasticsearch requires you to reindex the entire dataset to apply the change. For 100M documents, reindexing takes 6 hours. During that time, search serves stale results from the old index, or you took down search to rebuild. Fix: use blue-green indexing. Create a new index with the new settings, build it alongside the old one (reading from the same data source), and when the new index is ready, atomically swap the alias to point to the new index. Zero downtime, zero stale results. Elasticsearch aliases make this straightforward."},
       {name:"Too many shards — the cluster overhead explosion",desc:"You create 100 shards for an index with 10M documents (100K docs per shard). Each shard is a separate Lucene index with its own file handles, memory buffers, segment metadata, and thread pool. With 100 shards across 5 nodes, the cluster spends more time managing shard overhead than processing queries. Elasticsearch recommends 20–40GB per shard. For 10M documents (assuming ~1KB/doc = 10GB), you need 1 primary shard (10GB), not 100. Over-sharding is one of the most common Elasticsearch performance mistakes."},
       {name:"Not planning for index growth and rollover",desc:"You create one index for all your data. It grows to 500GB over a year. Queries slow down because large shards are expensive to search. Reindexing for mapping changes is impossible in a reasonable time. Fix: use time-based indices with rollover (e.g., logs-2024-01, logs-2024-02) or size-based rollover (create a new index when the current one hits 50GB). Elasticsearch Index Lifecycle Management (ILM) automates this: hot index for recent/active data, warm for older searchable data, cold for archival, delete after retention period."}
     ],
     examples:[
       {name:"GitHub code search — when off-the-shelf isn't enough",desc:"GitHub rebuilt their code search engine from scratch (internally called 'Blackbird') because Elasticsearch couldn't handle code-shaped queries at their scale (45M+ repositories, hundreds of billions of lines of code). Code search has unique requirements: regex matching, exact identifier lookup (find the function 'processPayment'), and language-aware tokenization (handling camelCase, snake_case, dots in package names). Blackbird uses a custom inverted index optimized for these patterns, built in Rust, achieving 10ms query times. Lesson: for common search patterns (e-commerce product search, blog article search, user lookup), off-the-shelf engines are excellent. For specialized search patterns at extreme scale, custom engines may be necessary — but this is a massive engineering investment."},
       {name:"Algolia for SaaS search — buying vs building",desc:"Many SaaS companies (Stripe's documentation search, Twitch's channel search, Slack's message search pre-scale) use Algolia rather than running Elasticsearch because the operational burden of self-hosted ES is significant: cluster management, JVM tuning, shard rebalancing, version upgrades, security patching. Algolia handles all of this for $1/1K search requests ($0.50/1K for records) with <10ms p99 latency globally. The tradeoff is clear: managed = expensive at scale but zero ops, self-hosted = cheaper at scale but significant operational investment. The crossover point is typically ~10M searches/month: below that, Algolia is easier; above that, self-hosted ES becomes economically attractive if you have the team to run it."},
       {name:"Meilisearch and Typesense — the Elasticsearch alternatives",desc:"Elasticsearch's operational complexity (JVM, cluster management, shard tuning) has created demand for simpler alternatives. Typesense (C++, single binary, no JVM — out-of-the-box typo tolerance, faceting, and ranking without configuration) and Meilisearch (Rust, developer-friendly API, instant search out of the box) both target the 'I need search but don't want to operate a cluster' use case. Both handle up to ~10M documents on a single node with <50ms latency. They're excellent choices for applications where search is important but not the core feature (e-commerce catalog, documentation search, admin panels). They struggle at the scale where Elasticsearch clusters shine (>100M documents, complex analytics-style queries, custom scoring)."}
     ],
     sizes_cfg:{
       small:{range:"<100K records, simple search (find products by name, search users by email)",rec:"Use PostgreSQL full-text search — it's built into the database you already have, requires no additional infrastructure, no synchronization, and no operational overhead. For simple LIKE queries on small tables (<10K rows), a basic B-tree index on the column is fine. For full-text search: add a tsvector column, create a GIN index, and query with to_tsquery. For fuzzy matching (typo tolerance): enable the pg_trgm extension and create a GIN trigram index — this allows similarity-based matching. Technology: PostgreSQL tsvector/tsquery (built-in full-text search — supports stemming, ranking, and language-specific parsing), pg_trgm (built-in extension for trigram-based fuzzy matching — 'find records similar to this string'), SQLite FTS5 (if you're on SQLite — surprisingly capable full-text search engine built into SQLite). All of these require zero additional infrastructure and are adequate for 'search within my app' use cases where search isn't the primary feature.",tools:["Postgres FTS (tsvector)","pg_trgm for fuzzy","SQLite FTS5"]},
       medium:{range:"100K–10M records, relevance ranking needed, autocomplete/suggest",rec:"PostgreSQL FTS with GIN indexes handles up to ~5M records well. Beyond that, or if you need faceted search, autocomplete, or sophisticated relevance ranking: add a dedicated search engine. Technology comparison: Elasticsearch (the industry standard — most powerful, most flexible, largest ecosystem; weakness: operationally heavy, JVM tuning required, cluster management). OpenSearch (AWS-managed fork of Elasticsearch — functionally equivalent, avoids Elastic's license changes; available as a managed service on AWS). Typesense (C++ — dead-simple to deploy, out-of-the-box typo tolerance, beautiful instant-search UI components; weakness: single-node only, limited to ~10M docs). Meilisearch (Rust — similar to Typesense, developer-friendly API, auto-detects language; weakness: single-node, not suitable for very large datasets). Algolia (SaaS — fastest time-to-working-search, excellent UI libraries, global infrastructure; weakness: expensive at scale, $1/1K searches). For async indexing: Debezium (CDC from PostgreSQL to Kafka) + Kafka Connect Elasticsearch Sink — the standard pipeline for keeping a search index in sync with your database.",tools:["Elasticsearch/OpenSearch","Typesense","Meilisearch","Algolia","Debezium for indexing"]},
       large:{range:"10M–1B records, complex queries, high throughput",rec:"Elasticsearch cluster (3–9+ nodes). Separate the indexing pipeline from the query path — indexing nodes handle write load, query nodes handle search requests. Use Logstash or Kafka Connect for async indexing from your primary database. Tune shards: 1 shard per 20–40GB of data. Technology: Elasticsearch 8 (latest — adds vector search / kNN for semantic similarity, improved security defaults, reduced JVM heap requirements). OpenSearch 2.x (AWS fork — compatible with Elasticsearch 7.x APIs, adds ML-powered relevance, anomaly detection). For the indexing pipeline: Debezium (CDC from any database) → Kafka → Kafka Connect Elasticsearch Sink connector. This is the standard production pipeline — Debezium captures every INSERT/UPDATE/DELETE from the DB's transaction log and publishes it to Kafka; the Elasticsearch sink connector consumes from Kafka and indexes into ES. Latency: 1–10 seconds from DB write to searchable. For query optimization: use Elasticsearch's query caching (node-level filter cache), shard request cache (per-shard result cache), and field data cache (for aggregations).",tools:["Elasticsearch 8 / OpenSearch","Kafka + Debezium for indexing","Logstash","shard tuning"]},
       hyper:{range:">1B records, sub-10ms latency, global deployment, semantic search",rec:"At this scale, search is typically a multi-stage pipeline: (1) Recall stage: fast, approximate retrieval using an inverted index (finds candidate documents) + vector ANN search (finds semantically similar documents) — returns top 1,000 candidates in <5ms. (2) Ranking stage: a machine learning model re-ranks the candidates for relevance, freshness, personalization — returns top 50 in <5ms. (3) Serving: results delivered from the nearest PoP. Technology: Custom Lucene-based search (Elasticsearch is built on Lucene — at extreme scale, companies build custom search services directly on Lucene for more control). Vespa (Yahoo's open-source search engine — combines text search + vector search + ML ranking in one system; used by Spotify, Yahoo, and many others; excellent for hybrid search). For vector/semantic search: embed documents using a model (OpenAI text-embedding-3-small, Cohere embed-v3), store embeddings in a vector index (FAISS, ScaNN, or Elasticsearch's built-in kNN), and combine vector similarity with traditional BM25 for hybrid search. Custom ML ranking: train a re-ranker on your click-through data (LambdaMART, cross-encoder transformers) and apply it in the ranking stage. This is how Google, Bing, and Amazon search work — the inverted index is just the first stage.",tools:["Custom Lucene-based","Vespa","FAISS/ScaNN for vectors","ML re-ranking","Elasticsearch kNN"]}
     },
     levelUp:[
       {from:"small",to:"medium",trigger:">1M records in searchable tables, OR users need relevance-ranked results (not just exact matches), OR autocomplete/type-ahead is a product requirement, OR pg_trgm fuzzy matching is too slow",action:"Add a dedicated search engine with async indexing from your primary database. How to do it: (1) Choose your engine: Typesense for simplicity (single binary, no config needed), Elasticsearch for power (complex queries, faceting, analytics), or Algolia if you want managed. (2) Define your search schema: which fields are searchable, which are filterable, which are sortable. (3) Build the initial index by batch-loading all existing records from the DB into the search engine (a one-time script). (4) Set up ongoing sync: for simplicity, a cron job every 5 minutes that queries 'records updated since last sync' and upserts them into the search engine. For robustness, use Debezium CDC → Kafka → search engine connector — captures every DB change automatically with 1–10s latency. (5) Update your application: search queries go to the search engine; write operations go to the primary DB only (the sync pipeline updates the search index asynchronously)."},
       {from:"medium",to:"large",trigger:">10M records OR search p99 >200ms OR you need complex aggregations/faceting that a single search node can't handle",action:"Scale to an Elasticsearch/OpenSearch cluster. Separate index nodes from query nodes. Tune shard count. How to do it: (1) Deploy a 3-node minimum cluster (for master election quorum). For dedicated roles: 3 master-eligible nodes (small instances, just for cluster coordination), N data/query nodes (sized for your data volume and query throughput). (2) Reindex with proper shard count: total_data_size / 30GB = number of primary shards. Set number_of_replicas: 1 for most use cases (each shard has one copy for HA). (3) Separate the indexing pipeline from query traffic: dedicate some nodes to indexing (receives writes from Kafka) and others to queries (receives search requests from the API). Use node attributes and allocation awareness to enforce this. (4) Implement blue-green reindexing: when you need to change mappings or analyzers, create a new index with the new configuration, reindex data into it, and swap the alias atomically (POST _aliases { actions: [{ remove: ...}, { add: ...}] })."},
       {from:"large",to:"hyper",trigger:">1B documents OR sub-10ms latency required globally OR semantic/vector search is a core requirement",action:"Build a two-stage search pipeline: recall (fast candidate retrieval) + ranking (ML-based re-ordering). How to do it: (1) Recall stage: maintain both an inverted index (BM25 text search) and a vector index (ANN for semantic similarity). For hybrid search, use Elasticsearch 8's kNN feature (combines BM25 and vector scores), or Vespa (native hybrid search). (2) Ranking stage: train a cross-encoder re-ranker on your click-through logs (cross-encoder models from Hugging Face, fine-tuned on your domain). Deploy as a lightweight inference service that re-ranks the top 100 candidates from the recall stage. (3) For global deployment: replicate the search index to each region (Elasticsearch Cross-Cluster Replication, or separate clusters per region synced via your indexing pipeline). Route users to the nearest search cluster via GeoDNS. (4) For vector embeddings: embed documents during the indexing pipeline (run embedding model on new/updated documents), store both the embedding vector and the text in your search engine, and at query time, embed the query and search both the vector index and the text index, then merge results."}
     ],
     children:[]}
  ]
};
